well as to the other symposium

00:00:54.950 --> 00:00:57.310
organizers who've done a
tremendous job putting this

00:00:57.310 --> 00:00:59.920
together, as well as to
Linda Cabot at Anderson

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:01.860
for the support
for this symposium.

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:04.599
For me personally, it's been
an absolutely amazing day.

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:06.130
I've learned a
tremendous amount,

00:01:06.130 --> 00:01:08.380
and I feel honored and
privileged to be a part of it

00:01:08.380 --> 00:01:10.920
and to have heard so many of
these distinguished speakers

00:01:10.920 --> 00:01:12.407
that we've had here today.

00:01:12.407 --> 00:01:14.990
I'd like to just take a second
before I introduce our speakers

00:01:14.990 --> 00:01:17.930
for this panel to reflect a
little bit on the sessions

00:01:17.930 --> 00:01:20.010
that we've already had,
to tie it in full circle

00:01:20.010 --> 00:01:22.040
to where we're about to go now.

00:01:22.040 --> 00:01:24.600
And I think back to the
origin of life panel

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:26.370
that started the day.

00:01:26.370 --> 00:01:30.490
And then we ended up working
into the physical interaction

00:01:30.490 --> 00:01:32.517
between the oceans
and our climate.

00:01:32.517 --> 00:01:34.350
Now we're going to kind
of come full circle.

00:01:34.350 --> 00:01:36.930
We're going to look back
at that life in the ocean,

00:01:36.930 --> 00:01:38.846
and we're going to take
a little bit of a look

00:01:38.846 --> 00:01:41.064
at how these pressures
and impacts, disturbances,

00:01:41.064 --> 00:01:42.980
acute and chronic--
although I think our panel

00:01:42.980 --> 00:01:45.350
is primarily interested
in chronic stress,

00:01:45.350 --> 00:01:47.360
or maybe some acute
disturbances that come along

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:50.560
with it-- on how that impacts
the oceans, how that impacts

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:55.030
the ecosystems and the species
that inhabit our oceans.

00:01:55.030 --> 00:01:57.190
So one note that I
found really interesting

00:01:57.190 --> 00:01:59.570
in thinking about the oceans
and reflecting earlier

00:01:59.570 --> 00:02:01.600
was Dr. Girguis's talk.

00:02:01.600 --> 00:02:05.330
He talked about the incredible
diversity in form and function

00:02:05.330 --> 00:02:07.080
in our oceans.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:10.000
There is, in every
nook and cranny,

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.550
every possible organism
you can imagine, just

00:02:12.550 --> 00:02:15.730
in terms of size,
shape, mechanics,

00:02:15.730 --> 00:02:18.732
physiology, the
ability to withstand

00:02:18.732 --> 00:02:20.940
some of the pressures of
living in the ocean already.

00:02:20.940 --> 00:02:22.981
Even without human impact,
it's not an easy place

00:02:22.981 --> 00:02:24.230
to live in and evolve.

00:02:24.230 --> 00:02:29.610
So the ability of to
respirate, salt-- osmoregulate,

00:02:29.610 --> 00:02:32.000
locomotory skills,
all these things.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.280
There's just an amazing
diversity in the ocean.

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:37.050
So now you throw in human
anthropogenic disturbances

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:41.650
into the mix, and it's
really quite incredible

00:02:41.650 --> 00:02:45.070
how much damage that can cause
over a very short time span.

00:02:45.070 --> 00:02:47.060
And as you'll see
momentarily, there

00:02:47.060 --> 00:02:49.530
are case studies from
right here in our backyard.

00:02:49.530 --> 00:02:51.710
I think it was
Lynne Talley's talk

00:02:51.710 --> 00:02:56.940
where she mentioned how
climate change is really--

00:02:56.940 --> 00:02:59.880
or, I should say, global
warming is really ocean warming

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:02.369
as so much of the warming
is reflected in our oceans.

00:03:02.369 --> 00:03:04.160
And we've no better a
case study than right

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:05.620
here in the Gulf of Maine.

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:07.980
And that's a good way to
lead into our first speaker

00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:09.230
for this panel.

00:03:09.230 --> 00:03:12.780
Dr. Andy Pershing is the
chief scientific officer

00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:15.940
up at the Gulf of Maine Research
Institute, also known as GMRI.

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:19.620
He also runs the ecosystem
modeling laboratory there.

00:03:19.620 --> 00:03:23.950
And his expertise is looking
at the causes and consequences

00:03:23.950 --> 00:03:27.969
of climate trends
and climate change

00:03:27.969 --> 00:03:29.760
here in the Gulf of
Maine and the Northwest

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:32.180
Atlantic in general and has
done a lot of amazing work

00:03:32.180 --> 00:03:33.763
in that realm, which
he'll talk to you

00:03:33.763 --> 00:03:34.910
a little bit about today.

00:03:34.910 --> 00:03:39.020
Moving on to our second speaker,
Dr. Anne Cohen from the Woods

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:40.840
Hole Oceanographic Institution.

00:03:40.840 --> 00:03:43.900
Anne is an internationally
renowned scientist

00:03:43.900 --> 00:03:46.940
who does work looking at the
effects of ocean acidification

00:03:46.940 --> 00:03:51.230
and warming, as well,
on ocean inhabitants,

00:03:51.230 --> 00:03:54.330
predominantly coral reefs and
then, as you'll learn today,

00:03:54.330 --> 00:03:56.990
some of the animals here
in our own backyard.

00:03:56.990 --> 00:04:01.000
And then finally, we're going
to get to hear Dr. Chris Clark.

