00:04:02.650 --> 00:04:04.066
Your title's a
little complicated.

00:04:06.971 --> 00:04:07.470
Just Chris.

00:04:07.470 --> 00:04:08.350
All right.

00:04:08.350 --> 00:04:09.890
Chris.

00:04:09.890 --> 00:04:14.940
So Dr. Clark is the IP
Johnson Founding Director

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:17.390
at the Cornell Laboratory of
Ornithology's Bioacoustics

00:04:17.390 --> 00:04:19.454
Research Program and
a senior scientist

00:04:19.454 --> 00:04:21.370
in the Department of
Neurobiology and Behavior

00:04:21.370 --> 00:04:23.210
at Cornell.

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:25.730
Dr. Clark, I know of
his work because he's

00:04:25.730 --> 00:04:28.885
worked very closely with my
close colleague Dr. Scott Kraus

00:04:28.885 --> 00:04:31.510
at the New England Aquarium for
years looking at the endangered

00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:32.960
North Atlantic right whale.

00:04:32.960 --> 00:04:35.760
And while I think Chris's
basic expertise is looking

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:38.830
at acoustic signaling
or communication

00:04:38.830 --> 00:04:42.460
between organisms,
he's applied a lot

00:04:42.460 --> 00:04:46.410
of novel and very sophisticated
acoustic technologies

00:04:46.410 --> 00:04:49.460
to addressing some of the big
conservation issues facing

00:04:49.460 --> 00:04:52.600
our oceans, especially on
endangered species, including

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:53.770
whales and birds.

00:04:53.770 --> 00:04:56.520
So it's a real nice, diverse
mix of speakers today,

00:04:56.520 --> 00:04:58.860
I think, touching on
some different topics.

00:04:58.860 --> 00:05:00.522
And I really hope you enjoy it.

00:05:00.522 --> 00:05:02.480
With no further ado, I'll
welcome Dr. Pershing.

