- All right.

00:05:09.810 --> 00:05:11.870
Thank you for coming, and
thanks for inviting me.

00:05:11.870 --> 00:05:15.486
And it's great that everybody
stuck around after coffee.

00:05:15.486 --> 00:05:16.610
So my name's Andy Pershing.

00:05:16.610 --> 00:05:18.818
I'm the chief scientist at
the Gulf of Maine Research

00:05:18.818 --> 00:05:21.360
Institute, which is just up
the road in Portland, Maine.

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:23.920
So I'm going to give just
an overview of a few things.

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:27.080
I'm going to talk with a couple
of basics of climate change

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:29.050
and really try to
pick up some threads

00:05:29.050 --> 00:05:32.270
that some of the earlier
speakers presented.

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:34.069
I'm going to then turn
to our local waters

00:05:34.069 --> 00:05:35.610
and think about the
impact that we've

00:05:35.610 --> 00:05:37.930
seen of global warming
and the warming trends

00:05:37.930 --> 00:05:41.160
that we have observed
here in the Gulf of Maine.

00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:43.820
And then I'll talk about the
impact of those temperature

00:05:43.820 --> 00:05:45.430
changes on cod.

00:05:45.430 --> 00:05:46.647
Lobsters had to be cut.

00:05:46.647 --> 00:05:48.230
I'll talk a little
bit about lobsters,

00:05:48.230 --> 00:05:50.610
but I'm not going to give
the full lobster story today.

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:53.340
And then I'll talk
about how we're

00:05:53.340 --> 00:05:56.480
thinking about adaptation
in terms of fisheries

00:05:56.480 --> 00:05:57.500
and natural resources.

00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:00.019
And hopefully, it'll
be a nice complement

00:06:00.019 --> 00:06:01.810
to the great talk we
heard about adaptation

00:06:01.810 --> 00:06:05.240
on the human
infrastructure side.

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:07.310
So this is the
famous Keeling Curve.

00:06:07.310 --> 00:06:10.130
Everybody's seen this unless
you were a caveman who was just

00:06:10.130 --> 00:06:12.040
recently dethawed,
in which case,

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:13.850
this is why you were
recently dethawed.

00:06:13.850 --> 00:06:16.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:20.740
But the previous speakers
did a great job, I think,

00:06:20.740 --> 00:06:23.950
talking about the consequences
that rising levels of carbon

00:06:23.950 --> 00:06:27.120
dioxide are having on our
planet in terms of warming

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:30.410
temperatures, impact
in vulnerable places

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:33.540
like the Arctic, CO2
dissolving into the ocean,

00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:34.680
and things like that.

00:06:34.680 --> 00:06:36.340
It's really easy,
though, to think

00:06:36.340 --> 00:06:39.080
that these are surprises,
that somehow we're

00:06:39.080 --> 00:06:40.010
just discovering this.

00:06:40.010 --> 00:06:41.509
And, of course,
there are surprises,

00:06:41.509 --> 00:06:43.380
and it's really
important that we

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:46.115
need to document what's
going on out there.

00:06:46.115 --> 00:06:47.990
But one of the reasons
that we're doing this,

00:06:47.990 --> 00:06:49.823
that we're trying to
document all this work,

00:06:49.823 --> 00:06:52.070
is that it allows
us to actually test

00:06:52.070 --> 00:06:54.680
models and predictions
that were put together

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:55.921
20 or 30 years ago.

00:06:55.921 --> 00:06:57.420
And so what I want
to do is actually

00:06:57.420 --> 00:07:00.270
walk you through a very
quick test of a climate model

00:07:00.270 --> 00:07:03.362
because I think it's
really informative to think

00:07:03.362 --> 00:07:05.320
a little bit that the
science of climate change

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:06.720
is not a new science.

00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:08.320
In many ways, we're
following threads

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:11.790
that were laid down over 100
years ago, as far as the role

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:16.350
that carbon dioxide plays in
making this planet habitable.

00:07:16.350 --> 00:07:20.900
So we're going to
start by trying to test

00:07:20.900 --> 00:07:22.750
a prediction by James Hansen.

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:26.350
So in 1981, Hansen wrote
a really influential paper

00:07:26.350 --> 00:07:29.660
in Science magazine,
where he was working

00:07:29.660 --> 00:07:31.810
with an early climate model.

00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:35.550
And he made a prediction, based
on the trends in carbon dioxide

00:07:35.550 --> 00:07:38.130
that he was seeing at
the time and predictions

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:41.790
on how people would use carbon
over the next 30 or 40 years,

00:07:41.790 --> 00:07:45.040
that "anthropogenic carbon
dioxide warming should emerge

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:48.040
from the noise level
of climate variability

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:49.414
by the end of the century."

00:07:49.414 --> 00:07:50.830
So really what
he's saying is that

00:07:50.830 --> 00:07:53.180
by the end of the
20th century, that we

00:07:53.180 --> 00:07:56.050
should be able to look at
the record of temperature

00:07:56.050 --> 00:07:58.460
on the planet, and we should
be able to clearly see

00:07:58.460 --> 00:07:59.850
that there's a warming signal.

00:07:59.850 --> 00:08:03.100
And we should see that
signal standing out

00:08:03.100 --> 00:08:06.264
even among the
variability that we have.

00:08:06.264 --> 00:08:07.930
Then he also made
predictions, and these

00:08:07.930 --> 00:08:09.860
should sound familiar--
the "creation

00:08:09.860 --> 00:08:12.140
of drought-prone regions in
North America and Central

00:08:12.140 --> 00:08:12.639
Asia."

00:08:12.639 --> 00:08:15.940
So think about the talk that
talked about the amplification

00:08:15.940 --> 00:08:18.330
of the hydrologic cycle.

00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:20.990
And the "opening of the
fabled Northwest Passage."

00:08:20.990 --> 00:08:23.620
Think of the previous talk
with the very depressing shot

00:08:23.620 --> 00:08:26.870
of the cruise ship in
the Northwest Passage.

00:08:26.870 --> 00:08:30.250
So in 1981, this is
the temperature record

00:08:30.250 --> 00:08:32.123
that Jim Hansen would
have had available.

00:08:32.123 --> 00:08:33.539
And, in fact, his
group was really

00:08:33.539 --> 00:08:36.669
instrumental in putting together
many of these global datasets,

00:08:36.669 --> 00:08:38.659
including this one.

00:08:38.659 --> 00:08:42.570
And so you can see in 1981 that
the temperature in that year

00:08:42.570 --> 00:08:45.030
was only slightly higher
than the temperature that

00:08:45.030 --> 00:08:48.084
was measured in about 1942.

00:08:48.084 --> 00:08:50.000
And so yes, you could
say, well, maybe there's

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:50.842
a hint of a trend.

00:08:50.842 --> 00:08:52.675
But there's also quite
a bit of variability.

00:08:52.675 --> 00:08:54.980
And it would be very
hard to say that there

00:08:54.980 --> 00:08:57.980
is a conclusive
trend in that data.

00:08:57.980 --> 00:09:00.114
10 years later, some
continued warming.

00:09:00.114 --> 00:09:01.780
But I don't know,
maybe it's going down.

00:09:01.780 --> 00:09:02.738
Things are cooling off.

00:09:02.738 --> 00:09:04.350
It won't be too bad, right?

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:06.590
OK, well, of course
it's worse than that.

00:09:06.590 --> 00:09:11.240
By the year 2000, we're now
able to see a very clear trend

00:09:11.240 --> 00:09:12.700
in this data set.

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:14.320
So in many ways,
Hansen was starting

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:17.170
to make predictions using some
of the early climate models.

00:09:17.170 --> 00:09:19.220
And we can now test
those predictions.

00:09:19.220 --> 00:09:20.260
And Hansen was right.

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:22.550
And, of course, it continues.

00:09:22.550 --> 00:09:25.900
And we're now faced
with the warmest

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:31.190
year ever that humans, at least,
have measured on the planet.

00:09:31.190 --> 00:09:34.630
And we're thinking
about the consequences

00:09:34.630 --> 00:09:37.760
of persistent drought
in the southwest.

00:09:37.760 --> 00:09:40.140
We heard a great talk
about the consequences

00:09:40.140 --> 00:09:43.150
of loss of sea ice in the
Arctic and cruise ships going

00:09:43.150 --> 00:09:46.670
through the Northwest Passage.

00:09:46.670 --> 00:09:51.310
But one of the reasons why I
include this story in my talks

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:55.080
is because I'm going to take
some of the temperature records

00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:58.510
from climate projections and
start to think about the impact

00:09:58.510 --> 00:10:02.720
that the predicted temperatures
are going to have on species

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:03.770
that we care about.

00:10:03.770 --> 00:10:05.567
And so that Hansen
story is meant

00:10:05.567 --> 00:10:07.150
to give you a little
bit of confidence

00:10:07.150 --> 00:10:10.060
that global climate
models actually

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:12.990
can say something meaningful,
that we're not just making them

00:10:12.990 --> 00:10:15.050
up, it's not a Chinese
hoax, that there's

00:10:15.050 --> 00:10:18.170
real science behind this and
that we know what we're doing.

00:10:18.170 --> 00:10:21.010
So of course, there, I'm
showing two different scenarios.

00:10:21.010 --> 00:10:24.430
The red one is the high CO2,
business as usual emissions

00:10:24.430 --> 00:10:25.730
pathway that we're on.

00:10:25.730 --> 00:10:28.940
The blue one is a very
optimistic scenario where

00:10:28.940 --> 00:10:31.430
CO2 emissions are cut way back.

00:10:31.430 --> 00:10:33.420
And they have very
different pictures

00:10:33.420 --> 00:10:36.910
of what the future temperature
of the planet will look like.

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:38.840
But one of the things
I want to highlight

00:10:38.840 --> 00:10:42.080
is that over that
first 30-year period,

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:44.260
those two lines are
almost exactly the same.

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:46.360
It is very hard to
distinguish them.

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:49.100
So we really are dividing the
world into these two periods,

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:52.420
into this initial period of
the next 20 or 30 years, where

00:10:52.420 --> 00:10:55.230
we really have to adapt to
the changes that are already

00:10:55.230 --> 00:10:56.504
baked into the system.

00:10:56.504 --> 00:10:57.920
One of the things
I like to say is

00:10:57.920 --> 00:11:00.790
that the temperature that we
have on the planet this year

00:11:00.790 --> 00:11:03.620
is actually a consequence
of carbon dioxide

00:11:03.620 --> 00:11:08.130
that was emitted when Nirvana
was on tour in the early 1990s.

00:11:08.130 --> 00:11:10.210
But then we start to
think about choices

00:11:10.210 --> 00:11:12.960
that we can make that
will play out, then,

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:14.902
towards the end of this century.

00:11:14.902 --> 00:11:16.860
So I'm going to talk
about a temperature story,

00:11:16.860 --> 00:11:18.290
and Anne's going
to pick things up

00:11:18.290 --> 00:11:20.780
with a story about
ocean acidification.

00:11:20.780 --> 00:11:24.450
And we just heard a great
talk on sea level rise.

00:11:24.450 --> 00:11:26.840
So this is the Gulf of Maine.

00:11:26.840 --> 00:11:28.610
It does bear the
name Maine, but I

00:11:28.610 --> 00:11:31.026
think it's really important
to remember that it's not just

00:11:31.026 --> 00:11:33.890
Maine, that it's Massachusetts,
it's Nova Scotia, it's New

00:11:33.890 --> 00:11:36.990
Brunswick, and, yes, even
New Hampshire gets a piece.

00:11:36.990 --> 00:11:39.490
So it's a really
important body of water,

00:11:39.490 --> 00:11:42.470
and it's been a very important
and influential body of water

00:11:42.470 --> 00:11:46.310
in the settlement
of New England.

00:11:46.310 --> 00:11:48.180
So this is the
temperature record

00:11:48.180 --> 00:11:49.740
from the satellite
data going back

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:52.690
to 1982 of sea
surface temperature

00:11:52.690 --> 00:11:53.720
in the Gulf of Maine.

00:11:53.720 --> 00:11:55.950
So I'm showing it on
almost a weekly scale,

00:11:55.950 --> 00:11:57.180
so a lot of variability.

00:11:57.180 --> 00:11:59.570
That's that blue line
in the background.

00:11:59.570 --> 00:12:01.510
If you begin to take
annual averages,

00:12:01.510 --> 00:12:03.010
you get the gray dots.

00:12:03.010 --> 00:12:05.380
And you can see there's
some pattern, right?

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:07.830
There's kind of maybe
a five-year cycle or so

00:12:07.830 --> 00:12:12.510
that's going on in the 1980s,
a bit of a jump around 2000,

00:12:12.510 --> 00:12:16.285
and then things have warmed
up over the last few years.

00:12:16.285 --> 00:12:17.910
And we can start to
do some statistics.

00:12:17.910 --> 00:12:20.560
So if we fit a line,
that black line--

00:12:20.560 --> 00:12:22.590
that black line has
us warming at a rate

00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:27.880
over this 34-year period of
0.04 degrees Celsius per year.

00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:30.350
That's hard to fathom
what that means.

00:12:30.350 --> 00:12:32.360
That's four times the
global average rate.

00:12:32.360 --> 00:12:34.600
The global average
ocean warming rate

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:37.954
is 0.01 degree Celsius per
year over this same period.

00:12:37.954 --> 00:12:39.870
So we've been warming
over this period at four

00:12:39.870 --> 00:12:42.130
times the global average rate.

00:12:42.130 --> 00:12:43.910
But it gets better.

00:12:43.910 --> 00:12:48.110
So from 2004 through 2013, I
highlighted this 10 year period

00:12:48.110 --> 00:12:50.900
because it was a feature
that really stuck out once we

00:12:50.900 --> 00:12:52.820
started looking at this data.

00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:55.390
And over that period, we
warmed at almost a quarter

00:12:55.390 --> 00:13:00.240
of a degree Celsius per year
over that 10-year period.

00:13:00.240 --> 00:13:02.630
If you map the
trends over that 2004

00:13:02.630 --> 00:13:06.150
through 2013 period-- so red
in that figure at the top

00:13:06.150 --> 00:13:08.780
is an area that has a
steep warming trend.

00:13:08.780 --> 00:13:11.420
Blue would be an area
that has a cooling

00:13:11.420 --> 00:13:13.380
trend over that 10-year period.

00:13:13.380 --> 00:13:14.990
You can see that
there's roughly--

00:13:14.990 --> 00:13:16.990
there's a little bit more
red, but it's probably

00:13:16.990 --> 00:13:18.790
hard to see, than blue.

00:13:18.790 --> 00:13:20.690
But the Gulf of
Maine in our region

00:13:20.690 --> 00:13:22.930
really stands out
in terms of being

00:13:22.930 --> 00:13:25.660
bright, bright red,
along with places

00:13:25.660 --> 00:13:31.150
like the-- I guess I have a
pointer-- the Barents Sea off

00:13:31.150 --> 00:13:35.710
of Norway, region of Australia.

00:13:35.710 --> 00:13:38.740
So these all areas
that had similar trends

00:13:38.740 --> 00:13:40.090
over the last 10 years.

00:13:40.090 --> 00:13:42.700
But the Gulf of Maine
still stands out.

00:13:42.700 --> 00:13:44.440
So if you view this
as a histogram,

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:46.680
we are way out here
on the right-hand side

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:49.460
of that distribution, which
leads to the statistic

00:13:49.460 --> 00:13:51.420
that over that 10-year
period, we warmed faster

00:13:51.420 --> 00:13:53.370
than 99% of the global ocean.

00:13:53.370 --> 00:13:56.030
It was a 10-year warming
trend, a 10-year increase

00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:58.494
in temperature that very
few large marine ecosystems

00:13:58.494 --> 00:13:59.410
have ever experienced.

00:14:02.250 --> 00:14:04.100
So what has been
driving that trend?

00:14:04.100 --> 00:14:06.540
Well, in the Gulf
of Maine, we're

00:14:06.540 --> 00:14:08.744
just this really interesting
place on the planet.

00:14:08.744 --> 00:14:10.660
We're right at the
boundary between cold water

00:14:10.660 --> 00:14:14.360
and warm water and between cold
air masses and warm air masses.

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:20.070
And the shifts in those warm
air masses or water masses

00:14:20.070 --> 00:14:22.950
has a big impact on the
temperature that we have.

00:14:22.950 --> 00:14:25.000
So in particular, we
have a cold current

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:26.640
that comes in from Nova Scotia.

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:28.390
We have warm water
that can come in

00:14:28.390 --> 00:14:30.160
from off the continental shelf.

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:32.000
And then we have
the Gulf Stream,

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:35.600
which is riding out here off
of the continental shelf.

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:38.052
We have seen over the
last few years an increase

00:14:38.052 --> 00:14:39.510
in the latitude of
the Gulf Stream.

00:14:39.510 --> 00:14:43.140
It's been pushing further north.

00:14:43.140 --> 00:14:46.070
And when that happens, we
get a characteristic series

00:14:46.070 --> 00:14:48.810
of changes in the circulation.

00:14:48.810 --> 00:14:51.180
We get a decrease in
that cold current,

00:14:51.180 --> 00:14:53.880
and we get an increase in
the supply of warm water.

00:14:53.880 --> 00:14:55.380
So it's a lot like
a bathtub, where

00:14:55.380 --> 00:14:57.864
you adjust the temperature
by turning the warm up

00:14:57.864 --> 00:14:59.280
if you want it to
be warm, and you

00:14:59.280 --> 00:15:02.530
can turn the cold down if you
want it to be really warm.

00:15:02.530 --> 00:15:06.180
And so that's what's been
going on in the Gulf of Maine.

00:15:06.180 --> 00:15:08.300
But why has the Gulf
Stream been changing?

00:15:08.300 --> 00:15:11.530
Why have these
currents been changing?

00:15:11.530 --> 00:15:13.820
Well, here's the map that
I previously showed you

00:15:13.820 --> 00:15:17.160
that showed the warming
trends over the last 10 years.

00:15:17.160 --> 00:15:20.100
Here's a map that Vince Saba, a
colleague from the Geophysical

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:22.769
Fluid Dynamics Lab,
had in his paper.

00:15:22.769 --> 00:15:24.060
And he allowed me to modify it.

00:15:24.060 --> 00:15:27.350
And what I did was I took the
warming trends from his paper,

00:15:27.350 --> 00:15:29.790
where he was running a very
high-resolution climate

00:15:29.790 --> 00:15:31.260
model, the only
one that actually

00:15:31.260 --> 00:15:33.620
can resolve the continental
shelf in our area

00:15:33.620 --> 00:15:35.869
and really get that
shelf circulation that's

00:15:35.869 --> 00:15:37.660
so important to
maintaining the temperature

00:15:37.660 --> 00:15:38.534
in the Gulf of Maine.

00:15:38.534 --> 00:15:40.610
And it's the only model
that can get that right.

00:15:40.610 --> 00:15:44.220
And so what I did was I took
the warming trends out of his

00:15:44.220 --> 00:15:48.190
that he was projecting, and I
just divided by the mean trend.

00:15:48.190 --> 00:15:50.810
So the gray area up
here off of Greenland

00:15:50.810 --> 00:15:52.730
is an area-- it's not
that it's cooling,

00:15:52.730 --> 00:15:56.160
it's just not warming as
quickly as the global average.

00:15:56.160 --> 00:15:58.940
Whereas the Gulf of
Maine is warming faster

00:15:58.940 --> 00:16:00.450
than that global average.

00:16:00.450 --> 00:16:03.350
And so notice the correspondence
between the two images.

00:16:03.350 --> 00:16:09.220
Both of them have this warm,
cool, warm-- warm, cool, warm--

00:16:09.220 --> 00:16:10.550
pattern.

00:16:10.550 --> 00:16:13.770
So we are seeing very similar
dynamics playing out right now

00:16:13.770 --> 00:16:16.220
to what the climate models
suggest we should see over

00:16:16.220 --> 00:16:17.790
the next century.

00:16:17.790 --> 00:16:20.240
And the mechanism behind
that that's in the models

00:16:20.240 --> 00:16:22.450
and, we think,
also in the data is

00:16:22.450 --> 00:16:24.970
related to large-scale
changes in the North Atlantic

00:16:24.970 --> 00:16:29.400
circulation, ultimately tied to
increases in fresh water supply

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:31.450
and melting in
Greenland changing

00:16:31.450 --> 00:16:35.340
this meridional overturning
circulation and causing,

00:16:35.340 --> 00:16:38.240
instead of the ocean going
up and down, where you're

00:16:38.240 --> 00:16:40.820
sinking at the poles and
then rising elsewhere,

00:16:40.820 --> 00:16:43.410
we're putting more energy
into going around and around,

00:16:43.410 --> 00:16:46.030
which tends to kick that
warmer water into our region

00:16:46.030 --> 00:16:49.691
and reduce the
supply of cold water.

00:16:49.691 --> 00:16:50.190
OK.

00:16:50.190 --> 00:16:53.470
So now for the biology, since
this is a biology panel.

00:16:53.470 --> 00:16:55.210
So I'm going to talk
in depth about cod

00:16:55.210 --> 00:16:58.420
because it's arguably the most
important fishery in the United

00:16:58.420 --> 00:16:59.610
States.

00:16:59.610 --> 00:17:01.980
It was the first export
from New England.

00:17:01.980 --> 00:17:03.970
I heard somebody say
that the English made

00:17:03.970 --> 00:17:06.730
more money off of cod
exported from New England

00:17:06.730 --> 00:17:08.339
than the Spanish
did off of the gold

00:17:08.339 --> 00:17:10.088
that they were getting
from their colonies

00:17:10.088 --> 00:17:11.660
in South America.

00:17:11.660 --> 00:17:14.579
In the late 1800s,
after the Civil War,

00:17:14.579 --> 00:17:16.270
the US had a bounty on cod.

00:17:16.270 --> 00:17:19.490
We were catching over
70,000 tons of cod

00:17:19.490 --> 00:17:22.310
from this Gulf of Maine
stock in a single year.

00:17:22.310 --> 00:17:23.940
So remember that number.

00:17:23.940 --> 00:17:28.560
In 2014, catch limits were
reduced to about 350 tons

00:17:28.560 --> 00:17:29.780
for the Gulf of Maine stock.

00:17:29.780 --> 00:17:33.560
So a very, very steep
decline in this population.

00:17:33.560 --> 00:17:35.870
And here's what that
steep declines looks like.

00:17:35.870 --> 00:17:40.280
So we had more fish
in the early 1980s.

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:42.170
We had less fish in the 1990s.

00:17:42.170 --> 00:17:44.240
And then we have
this big decline

00:17:44.240 --> 00:17:48.570
that started in the late 2000s.

00:17:48.570 --> 00:17:50.690
Well, what was
driving that decline?

00:17:50.690 --> 00:17:52.340
Well, one of the
things that we look

00:17:52.340 --> 00:17:54.250
for when you're trying to
diagnose what's going on

00:17:54.250 --> 00:17:56.750
with a fish population is you
look at the number of new fish

00:17:56.750 --> 00:17:59.320
that are coming
into the population.

00:17:59.320 --> 00:18:00.900
We call this recruitment.

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:03.070
So this is an estimate
of the number of new fish

00:18:03.070 --> 00:18:05.090
that are being recruited
into the population.

00:18:05.090 --> 00:18:07.530
And you can see it
has a lot of parallels

00:18:07.530 --> 00:18:10.610
with the decline in biomass.

00:18:10.610 --> 00:18:12.396
But that's kind
of what we expect.

00:18:12.396 --> 00:18:13.770
If you have fewer
females, you're

00:18:13.770 --> 00:18:15.420
going to get fewer babies.

00:18:15.420 --> 00:18:19.200
And so in part, some of
that is going on in here.

00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:22.930
So what we did was we took
the data up through 2004,

00:18:22.930 --> 00:18:25.510
before the onset of
this rapid warming.

00:18:25.510 --> 00:18:28.120
And we fit two
statistical models

00:18:28.120 --> 00:18:31.040
that were trying to predict
the number of new fish entering

00:18:31.040 --> 00:18:34.530
the population based on
the number of females

00:18:34.530 --> 00:18:35.290
in the population.

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:39.410
And then we fit
another model that

00:18:39.410 --> 00:18:41.000
included a temperature effect.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:42.730
So we have two different models.

00:18:42.730 --> 00:18:46.210
Both of them do almost equally
well during this period.

00:18:46.210 --> 00:18:49.360
But they perform
very differently

00:18:49.360 --> 00:18:52.750
when we confront them with
the new data after 2004.

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:54.940
If we don't include
that temperature effect,

00:18:54.940 --> 00:18:58.140
we greatly overestimate the
recruitment in the population.

00:18:58.140 --> 00:19:00.390
As a consequence, we
greatly overestimate

00:19:00.390 --> 00:19:04.380
the potential productivity
of that stock.

00:19:04.380 --> 00:19:06.780
And if we include a
temperature effect,

00:19:06.780 --> 00:19:09.280
we actually explain
the decline of cod.

00:19:09.280 --> 00:19:11.620
So temperature was
a major contributor

00:19:11.620 --> 00:19:14.020
to the decline in recruitment
and to the decline

00:19:14.020 --> 00:19:15.940
in this population.

00:19:15.940 --> 00:19:17.620
But it wasn't just
temperature alone.

00:19:17.620 --> 00:19:20.730
It was really the interaction
between temperature and people.

00:19:20.730 --> 00:19:23.700
So fisheries management is
meant to be a negative feedback

00:19:23.700 --> 00:19:26.980
loop, meaning that if there's
a change in the population--

00:19:26.980 --> 00:19:30.920
let's say there are fewer fish--
we pick them up in our sensors

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:33.350
and in our process called
the stock assessment.

00:19:33.350 --> 00:19:35.640
And we say, oh,
there are fewer fish.

00:19:35.640 --> 00:19:38.770
We then pass that through
the management machinery.

00:19:38.770 --> 00:19:41.960
And at the end, we come up
with quotas or regulations

00:19:41.960 --> 00:19:44.530
that reduce the fishing
pressure on that stock

00:19:44.530 --> 00:19:47.240
and should allow that
stock to increase.

00:19:47.240 --> 00:19:49.090
Well, over the last
few years, we've

00:19:49.090 --> 00:19:52.191
been in this cycle where every
time we look at the stock,

00:19:52.191 --> 00:19:54.190
there are fewer fish than
we thought there were.

00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:57.110
And not only that, there were
fewer fish the previous year

00:19:57.110 --> 00:19:59.657
than we thought there were
when we looked at them then.

00:19:59.657 --> 00:20:00.615
Very, very challenging.

00:20:00.615 --> 00:20:04.710
And what our study shows is
that the ocean was really

00:20:04.710 --> 00:20:07.930
changing the dynamics faster
than this human system

00:20:07.930 --> 00:20:08.990
could keep up.

00:20:08.990 --> 00:20:11.440
And so we were issuing
quotas, and fishermen

00:20:11.440 --> 00:20:13.060
were staying within
those quotas,

00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:14.670
yet overfishing
was still occurring

00:20:14.670 --> 00:20:17.020
because the science
wasn't able to keep up

00:20:17.020 --> 00:20:20.110
with the changes in the ocean.

00:20:20.110 --> 00:20:22.235
But I don't think
it's all terrible.

00:20:22.235 --> 00:20:23.610
So I'm going to
talk a little bit

00:20:23.610 --> 00:20:24.776
about the future of the cod.

00:20:24.776 --> 00:20:27.510
And this is where those climate
models are going to come in.

00:20:27.510 --> 00:20:29.150
So this is where we are.

00:20:29.150 --> 00:20:31.240
The black line is
our current level

00:20:31.240 --> 00:20:33.200
of spawning stock biomass.

00:20:33.200 --> 00:20:35.564
The dashed line is where
management thinks we should be.

00:20:35.564 --> 00:20:37.980
This is the goal that the New
England Fisheries Management

00:20:37.980 --> 00:20:40.340
Council has for the stock.

00:20:40.340 --> 00:20:41.140
OK.

00:20:41.140 --> 00:20:45.210
So keep in mind, that's
about 55,000 tons of fish,

00:20:45.210 --> 00:20:49.150
where in the late 1800s, we were
catching 70,000 tons of fish.

00:20:49.150 --> 00:20:51.520
So there's been a very
big change in scale

00:20:51.520 --> 00:20:53.670
in our expectations
for this stock.

00:20:53.670 --> 00:20:57.520
But this doesn't include
the impact of temperature.

00:20:57.520 --> 00:21:00.240
So if we add a
temperature effect,

00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:03.960
we bring down our expectation
for the stock because they're

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:06.070
going to be less productive.

00:21:06.070 --> 00:21:08.260
So now we're going to
project things forward.

00:21:08.260 --> 00:21:11.110
So if we allow a little
bit of fishing and project

00:21:11.110 --> 00:21:13.330
under our mean warming
from the climate model

00:21:13.330 --> 00:21:15.410
projections over this
period, we actually

00:21:15.410 --> 00:21:17.710
can get an increase
in the population.

00:21:20.870 --> 00:21:23.750
But we never rebuild to
what is our current target.

00:21:23.750 --> 00:21:27.140
But if we apply the same
temperature to our reference

00:21:27.140 --> 00:21:29.030
points, to our
management targets,

00:21:29.030 --> 00:21:31.650
we would actually say
that we could rebuild

00:21:31.650 --> 00:21:35.300
this stock by about 2028.

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:36.030
So not too bad.

00:21:36.030 --> 00:21:38.790
Not too far outside
of the 10-year horizon

00:21:38.790 --> 00:21:41.230
that's the goal in
management right now.

00:21:41.230 --> 00:21:42.840
But that's only one temperature.

00:21:42.840 --> 00:21:45.030
And we know that there's
a range of temperatures

00:21:45.030 --> 00:21:46.850
that we could experience.

00:21:46.850 --> 00:21:49.870
We could have cooler
temperatures--

00:21:49.870 --> 00:21:53.760
not the temperatures
get cool, but we

00:21:53.760 --> 00:21:56.260
warm at a more gradual rate.

00:21:56.260 --> 00:21:59.970
Or we could stay on this
rapid-- on our 30-year warming

00:21:59.970 --> 00:22:03.252
trend, which I'm calling
the warm case down here.

00:22:03.252 --> 00:22:04.960
And you might look at
this graph and say,

00:22:04.960 --> 00:22:08.200
wow, we should really
be hoping for warm water

00:22:08.200 --> 00:22:10.850
because with warm water, we
could say that we could rebuild

00:22:10.850 --> 00:22:13.290
a few years earlier, that
we could declare victory

00:22:13.290 --> 00:22:14.560
and go home.

00:22:14.560 --> 00:22:16.566
Of course, it doesn't
work that way.

00:22:16.566 --> 00:22:18.440
You have to take into
account the temperature

00:22:18.440 --> 00:22:20.910
on the productivity
of the stock, as well.

00:22:20.910 --> 00:22:23.560
And so in the warming
case, we wouldn't actually

00:22:23.560 --> 00:22:27.460
rebuild until about 2034.

00:22:27.460 --> 00:22:29.780
So there's this interaction
between management

00:22:29.780 --> 00:22:33.690
and an interaction
between the ocean.

00:22:33.690 --> 00:22:35.350
If there were no
fishing, we obviously

00:22:35.350 --> 00:22:38.310
would increase the
population faster,

00:22:38.310 --> 00:22:43.590
but at very large
socioeconomic costs, as well.

00:22:43.590 --> 00:22:46.127
So just a few lessons that
I'd like to highlight.

00:22:46.127 --> 00:22:48.710
One of the things that I think
we can say in the Gulf of Maine

00:22:48.710 --> 00:22:51.140
is that global warming is real
and that it impacts things

00:22:51.140 --> 00:22:52.220
that we care about.

00:22:52.220 --> 00:22:55.312
It isn't just some
abstract concept

00:22:55.312 --> 00:22:56.770
that's out there
for people to talk

00:22:56.770 --> 00:22:59.190
about at wonderful
universities like this.

00:22:59.190 --> 00:23:01.680
It's real, and it's
impacting people's lives.

00:23:01.680 --> 00:23:04.730
And we've seen that especially
with the cod fishery, where

00:23:04.730 --> 00:23:06.410
communities in
Gloucester are really

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:09.420
grappling with a huge amount
of socioeconomic stress

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:11.790
due to the decline
of that fishery.

00:23:11.790 --> 00:23:14.630
Lobster is sort of a
different story, where

00:23:14.630 --> 00:23:16.300
we've seen, basically,
the collapse

00:23:16.300 --> 00:23:19.520
of the fishery in Rhode Island
and in southern New England.

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:21.724
But in Maine,
lobster is booming.

00:23:21.724 --> 00:23:23.140
The lobster fishery
in Maine alone

00:23:23.140 --> 00:23:25.970
was worth over half a
billion dollars last year,

00:23:25.970 --> 00:23:28.400
a huge increase in the
population, a huge increase

00:23:28.400 --> 00:23:30.840
in the value of that stock.

00:23:30.840 --> 00:23:34.880
And there's a temperature story
that's embedded in lobster.

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:38.550
We've seen northern
shrimp-- very similar

00:23:38.550 --> 00:23:40.090
global distribution to cod.

00:23:40.090 --> 00:23:43.880
And not surprisingly, we've
had a collapse in that fishery,

00:23:43.880 --> 00:23:47.329
as well, that's very
much due to temperature.

00:23:47.329 --> 00:23:49.120
On the other hand,
we're seeing an increase

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:51.660
in species like black
sea bass, especially here

00:23:51.660 --> 00:23:52.620
in Massachusetts.

00:23:52.620 --> 00:23:55.590
We're seeing longfin squid
moving into the Gulf of Maine.

00:23:55.590 --> 00:23:57.900
And these are potential
commercial species

00:23:57.900 --> 00:24:00.590
that may make up for
some of the loss of some

00:24:00.590 --> 00:24:02.146
of these other things.

00:24:02.146 --> 00:24:06.130
So the previous talk, I
think, did a great job

00:24:06.130 --> 00:24:08.760
of sort of laying out that
kind of the adaptation

00:24:08.760 --> 00:24:11.680
challenges that a city
is having to deal with.

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:15.490
We're trying to understand what
are the adaptation challenges

00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:18.132
that fishing communities and
that fisheries management

00:24:18.132 --> 00:24:18.840
has to deal with.

00:24:18.840 --> 00:24:22.070
And a lot of it has to do with
thinking about decisions that

00:24:22.070 --> 00:24:24.850
get made by different actors
at different space and time

00:24:24.850 --> 00:24:25.720
scales.

00:24:25.720 --> 00:24:28.336
So a fisherman has to
decide whether they're

00:24:28.336 --> 00:24:30.960
going to stay in the fishery or
whether they're going to leave.

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:32.810
The fishing community
has to make decisions

00:24:32.810 --> 00:24:34.314
about their infrastructure.

00:24:34.314 --> 00:24:35.980
They have to think
about sea level rise,

00:24:35.980 --> 00:24:37.220
but they also have
to think about

00:24:37.220 --> 00:24:39.594
are they going to continue to
support commercial fishing,

00:24:39.594 --> 00:24:44.170
or are they going to put in
a marina and support yachts.

00:24:44.170 --> 00:24:46.460
For fisheries
management, how can we

00:24:46.460 --> 00:24:50.270
account for trends similar to
what we've done and with cod?

00:24:50.270 --> 00:24:51.856
Is there a way to
develop forecasts

00:24:51.856 --> 00:24:53.230
that might be able
to give advice

00:24:53.230 --> 00:24:56.820
on the medium-term about
how to manage fisheries?

00:24:56.820 --> 00:24:58.600
And what are the
strategies that we can

00:24:58.600 --> 00:25:01.550
take to manage for resilience?

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:03.940
So just some quick
summary points.

00:25:03.940 --> 00:25:05.980
The Gulf of Maine
is warming rapidly.

00:25:05.980 --> 00:25:09.540
The warming has already impacted
human and natural communities.

00:25:09.540 --> 00:25:11.760
The adaptation
requires, first of all,

00:25:11.760 --> 00:25:14.690
acknowledging that climate
change is having an impact.

00:25:14.690 --> 00:25:16.800
But good management
can build resilience.

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:18.820
So there is an
opportunity to make sure

00:25:18.820 --> 00:25:21.410
that the fisheries that we have
can be sustainable in a warmer

00:25:21.410 --> 00:25:23.660
climate, as long as we
knowledge that the climate is

00:25:23.660 --> 00:25:24.830
going to be warmer.

00:25:24.830 --> 00:25:26.130
So thank you.

00:25:26.130 --> 00:25:29.098
