01:18:00.620 --> 01:18:03.610
- Thank you very much, Dr.
Clark, and to our whole panel

01:18:03.610 --> 01:18:05.090
for these excellent
presentations.

01:18:05.090 --> 01:18:07.990
So now we have time,
before our final session,

01:18:07.990 --> 01:18:10.740
for two questions
from the audience.

01:18:10.740 --> 01:18:13.325
Adam Sacks again, since
nobody else is here.

01:18:13.325 --> 01:18:17.500
I want to ask Dr. Clark
about your findings

01:18:17.500 --> 01:18:28.430
among the animals whose shells
are just being defective.

01:18:28.430 --> 01:18:31.520
Aren't we seeing natural
selection right in front

01:18:31.520 --> 01:18:33.930
of our very eyes there?

01:18:33.930 --> 01:18:39.270
And over generations, have
you done a longitudinal kind

01:18:39.270 --> 01:18:42.230
of study over generations
of those creatures-- I don't

01:18:42.230 --> 01:18:46.890
know if it's possible--
and see if you

01:18:46.890 --> 01:18:50.320
develop a population that's
resistant to acidification?

01:18:54.662 --> 01:18:56.420
- I think the
question is for me?

01:18:56.420 --> 01:18:56.920
- Yes.

01:18:56.920 --> 01:18:57.576
- Is this on?

01:18:57.576 --> 01:18:58.430
- Yes

01:18:58.430 --> 01:19:00.750
- Yes.

01:19:00.750 --> 01:19:04.230
- That's a really good question.

01:19:04.230 --> 01:19:05.390
I think we are.

01:19:05.390 --> 01:19:09.710
Humans are definitely performing
a natural selection experiment.

01:19:09.710 --> 01:19:11.970
The question is, is
it going to work?

01:19:11.970 --> 01:19:15.520
I mean, the level of
uncertainty there, I think,

01:19:15.520 --> 01:19:18.860
is one of the scary
parts of this.

01:19:18.860 --> 01:19:20.570
Natural selection
also usually happens

01:19:20.570 --> 01:19:23.950
over very long time periods.

01:19:23.950 --> 01:19:28.720
And what we're doing is
really escalating the rate

01:19:28.720 --> 01:19:30.750
at which things are happening.

01:19:30.750 --> 01:19:33.030
As far-- your
question with respect

01:19:33.030 --> 01:19:38.050
to have we grown these organisms
out through several generations

01:19:38.050 --> 01:19:40.550
to see if natural
selection can occur,

01:19:40.550 --> 01:19:41.800
not with the sea scallops.

01:19:41.800 --> 01:19:47.370
And in fact, ours was the first
successful ocean acidification

01:19:47.370 --> 01:19:48.810
experiment with
sea scallops just

01:19:48.810 --> 01:19:51.380
because they're so
difficult to rear

01:19:51.380 --> 01:19:53.300
under experimental conditions.

01:19:53.300 --> 01:19:57.210
And so we actually
invested several years

01:19:57.210 --> 01:20:00.520
into figuring out how
to actually grow them

01:20:00.520 --> 01:20:04.250
in the laboratory so that we
did have a successful grow out

01:20:04.250 --> 01:20:06.640
under ambient conditions,
and then started

01:20:06.640 --> 01:20:08.770
to introduce them to
treatments after that.

01:20:08.770 --> 01:20:12.490
So in fact, even though
I'm sort of showing the end

01:20:12.490 --> 01:20:15.410
results of these
experiments, it takes

01:20:15.410 --> 01:20:20.470
a long time, a lot of
effort, quite a bit of money

01:20:20.470 --> 01:20:23.260
to come up with
really robust results

01:20:23.260 --> 01:20:28.855
that we feel confident that we
can put into these projection

01:20:28.855 --> 01:20:30.210
models.

01:20:30.210 --> 01:20:34.330
So we're kind of at
the cusp of this.

01:20:34.330 --> 01:20:36.616
There also isn't an
endless amount of money.

01:20:36.616 --> 01:20:38.490
This is another thing
you have to understand.

01:20:38.490 --> 01:20:41.620
I mean, NOAA, who is running
the ocean acidification

01:20:41.620 --> 01:20:45.870
program, who actually funds
our sea scallop experiments,

01:20:45.870 --> 01:20:47.400
they're cut.

01:20:47.400 --> 01:20:51.250
And funds are thin,
spread thin on the ground.

01:20:51.250 --> 01:20:57.340
So we've submitted a
proposal to an open call

01:20:57.340 --> 01:21:01.620
to do exactly that, to test out
different populations of sea

01:21:01.620 --> 01:21:05.970
scallops to see whether we
can see natural variability

01:21:05.970 --> 01:21:08.440
and sensitivity across
different populations.

01:21:08.440 --> 01:21:10.440
I'm going to have to
submit that proposal again.

01:21:10.440 --> 01:21:11.160
- Right.

01:21:11.160 --> 01:21:17.080
But they're not going to wait
to evolve for you to get funded.

01:21:17.080 --> 01:21:17.580
- I know.

01:21:17.580 --> 01:21:18.080
Damn.

01:21:18.080 --> 01:21:19.460
- I absolutely
support the study.

01:21:19.460 --> 01:21:22.800
But if the acidification
is increasing,

01:21:22.800 --> 01:21:25.800
then you're going to
get that selection.

01:21:25.800 --> 01:21:28.620
It's going to be
gradually increasing along

01:21:28.620 --> 01:21:31.050
with the increasing
ocean acidification.

01:21:31.050 --> 01:21:36.150
And evolution with
fast-growing animals-- I mean,

01:21:36.150 --> 01:21:38.760
we see these things with
industrial moths in England

01:21:38.760 --> 01:21:40.570
and that sort of thing.

01:21:40.570 --> 01:21:42.680
They change pretty quick.

01:21:42.680 --> 01:21:44.200
And I don't know--

01:21:44.200 --> 01:21:47.050
- Well, we have examples from
history, from geologic time

01:21:47.050 --> 01:21:51.560
periods, of mass extinctions of
calcifiers under elevated CO2

01:21:51.560 --> 01:21:52.090
conditions.

01:21:52.090 --> 01:21:54.256
We know that these things
have occurred at least six

01:21:54.256 --> 01:21:55.531
times in the past.

01:21:55.531 --> 01:21:59.150
But the time scale for
those organisms to come back

01:21:59.150 --> 01:22:00.780
is a hell of a lot
longer than you're

01:22:00.780 --> 01:22:05.010
going to wait around for the
sea scallop in the restaurant--

01:22:05.010 --> 01:22:07.270
tens of thousands of years.

01:22:07.270 --> 01:22:10.130
So we're talking about a
brink of a mass extinction.

01:22:10.130 --> 01:22:11.930
Organisms, yes, they're
going to come back.

01:22:11.930 --> 01:22:14.100
Some organisms are
going to adapt.

01:22:14.100 --> 01:22:17.000
But the time frame
that we're looking at

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:19.550
is not the time frame
that we're operating on.

01:22:19.550 --> 01:22:21.490
